<figureCitation box="[1254,1337,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[239,1347,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-31@3.[239,1347,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Bermudacaris britayevi Anker, Poddoubtchenko &amp; Marin, 2006, ovigerous female (cl 3.0 mm) from Guam, Mariana Islands (FLMNH UF 54550), living shrimp shortly after collection: A—left lateral view; eggs (developing embryos) shed; B—right lateral view. Photographs by the author." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4729437" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4729437/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1352,1368,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[209,1378,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-16@4.[209,1378,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Bermudacaris britayevi Anker, Poddoubtchenko &amp; Marin, 2006, ovigerous female (cl 3.0 mm) from Guam, Mariana Islands (FLMNH UF 54550), living shrimp shortly after collection: A, B—dorsal view on lighter and darker backgrounds; C—ventral view on dark background. Photographs by the author." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4729439" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4729439/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">3</figureCitation>
). The most conspicuous bright red patches are present on the antennular peduncles, third maxillipeds, sixth pleonite and uropodal endopod. Smaller, more diffuse reddish areas can be seen on the carapace and eyestalks. The chelipeds are generally ivory white, with a yellow tinge near the fingers. The ovaries, visible due to the partial translucence of the tegument, are bright orange, which is also the colour of the developing eggs (
<figureCitation box="[1017,1108,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[239,1347,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-31@3.[239,1347,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Bermudacaris britayevi Anker, Poddoubtchenko &amp; Marin, 2006, ovigerous female (cl 3.0 mm) from Guam, Mariana Islands (FLMNH UF 54550), living shrimp shortly after collection: A—left lateral view; eggs (developing embryos) shed; B—right lateral view. Photographs by the author." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4729437" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4729437/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="59" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,150,1365]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,294,367,393]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">Ecology</emphasis>
. The Guam specimen was collected on a coral reef, on fine sand under a large piece of coral rubble at a depth of about 
<specimenCount box="[319,382,403,429]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59" type="generic">
<elevation box="[319,378,403,429]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="59" unit="m" value="10.0">10 m</elevation>
.
</specimenCount>
In contrast, the holotype was collected with a suction (yabby) pump on an intertidal sand-mud flat close to mangroves and was apparently associated with an unknown burrowing host (
<bibRefCitation author="Anker, A. &amp; Poddoubtchenko, D. &amp; Marin, I." box="[1152,1355,439,466]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59" pagination="1675 - 1686" refId="ref2807" refString="Anker, A., Poddoubtchenko, D. &amp; Marin, I. (2006) On the presence of the alpheid shrimp genus Bermudacaris Anker and Iliffe, 2000 (Crustacea: Decapoda: Caridea) in the Pacific Ocean, with description of a new species from Vietnam. Journal of Natural History, 40, 1675 - 1686. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930600937734" type="journal article" year="2006">
Anker 
<emphasis box="[1231,1287,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">et al.</emphasis>
2006
</bibRefCitation>
). Thus, the ecological plasticity of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Anker, Poddoubtchenko &amp; Marin" authorityYear="2006" box="[460,592,475,501]" class="Malacostraca" family="Alpheidae" genus="Bermudacaris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="britayevi">
<emphasis box="[460,592,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">B. britayevi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is rather unusual, although it cannot be excluded that the Guam specimen was also associated with a burrowing animal, since horizontal or oblique burrows are often exposed and partly destroyed by flipping over large, deeply embedded coral rocks.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="59" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,150,1365]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,583,609]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">Remarks</emphasis>
. Since one of the chelipeds (the right one) was lacking in the Vietnamese holotype of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Anker, Poddoubtchenko &amp; Marin" authorityYear="2006" box="[1297,1430,583,609]" class="Malacostraca" family="Alpheidae" genus="Bermudacaris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="britayevi">
<emphasis box="[1297,1430,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">B. britayevi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the different armature of the left (major) cheliped fingers in the 
<collectingCountry box="[865,933,619,645]" name="Guam" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">Guam</collectingCountry>
specimen could be interpreted as (1) general instraspecific variability of the chelipeds, i.e., the holotype may have had the right cheliped very similar to the left one, without strong teeth on the cutting edges; or (2) the species being generally characterised by the somewhat unequal and asymmetrical chelipeds, i.e. the holotype may have had lost the right (major) cheliped with strong teeth, very similar to the left (major) one of the 
<collectingCountry box="[618,686,763,789]" name="Guam" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">Guam</collectingCountry>
specimen. Possibility of sexual dimorphism can be excluded since the 
<typeStatus box="[192,290,799,825]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">holotype</typeStatus>
and the 
<collectingCountry box="[386,454,799,825]" name="Guam" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">Guam</collectingCountry>
specimen are both females.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,150,1365]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">
Not taking into the account the robustness of the chela and the finger dentition, the left (major) and right (minor) chelipeds of the 
<collectingCountry box="[337,405,871,897]" name="Guam" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">Guam</collectingCountry>
specimen are generally very similar between them and also between them and the left (minor) cheliped of the 
<typeStatus box="[380,482,907,933]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">holotype</typeStatus>
. In all other characters, including the disposition of the spiniform setae on the merus and carpus (
<figureCitation box="[287,373,943,969]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1938,1962]" captionTargetBox="[160,1397,209,1884]" captionTargetId="figure-16@2.[151,1436,179,1912]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bermudacaris britayevi Anker, Poddoubtchenko &amp; Marin, 2006, ovigerous female (cl 3.0 mm) from Guam, Mariana Islands (FLMNH UF 54550), left cheliped: A—entire cheliped, mesial view; B—same, lateral view; C—carpus, mesial view; D—carpus and chela, mesial view; E—same, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4729435" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4729435/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
) and the presence of one conspicuous, long, ventrally pointing, slender seta on the carpus (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1938,1962]" captionTargetBox="[160,1397,209,1884]" captionTargetId="figure-16@2.[151,1436,179,1912]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bermudacaris britayevi Anker, Poddoubtchenko &amp; Marin, 2006, ovigerous female (cl 3.0 mm) from Guam, Mariana Islands (FLMNH UF 54550), left cheliped: A—entire cheliped, mesial view; B—same, lateral view; C—carpus, mesial view; D—carpus and chela, mesial view; E—same, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4729435" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4729435/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">Fig. 1A, C</figureCitation>
), the chelipeds of the Vietnamese 
<typeStatus box="[595,693,979,1005]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">holotype</typeStatus>
and the 
<collectingCountry box="[785,853,979,1005]" name="Guam" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">Guam</collectingCountry>
specimen are almost identical (cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Anker, A. &amp; Poddoubtchenko, D. &amp; Marin, I." box="[1236,1432,979,1005]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59" pagination="1675 - 1686" refId="ref2807" refString="Anker, A., Poddoubtchenko, D. &amp; Marin, I. (2006) On the presence of the alpheid shrimp genus Bermudacaris Anker and Iliffe, 2000 (Crustacea: Decapoda: Caridea) in the Pacific Ocean, with description of a new species from Vietnam. Journal of Natural History, 40, 1675 - 1686. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930600937734" type="journal article" year="2006">
Anker 
<emphasis box="[1312,1360,979,1005]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">et al</emphasis>
. 2006
</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 3). The slender spiniform setae on the ischium of the left (major) cheliped of the 
<collectingCountry box="[1088,1156,1015,1041]" name="Guam" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">Guam</collectingCountry>
specimen (
<figureCitation box="[1282,1366,1015,1041]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1938,1962]" captionTargetBox="[160,1397,209,1884]" captionTargetId="figure-16@2.[151,1436,179,1912]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bermudacaris britayevi Anker, Poddoubtchenko &amp; Marin, 2006, ovigerous female (cl 3.0 mm) from Guam, Mariana Islands (FLMNH UF 54550), left cheliped: A—entire cheliped, mesial view; B—same, lateral view; C—carpus, mesial view; D—carpus and chela, mesial view; E—same, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4729435" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4729435/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
) were drawn as two indistinct lines on the original pencil drawing and later interpreted as spiniform setae by the author based on their position in the 
<typeStatus box="[479,577,1087,1113]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Anker, A. &amp; Poddoubtchenko, D. &amp; Marin, I." box="[591,792,1087,1113]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59" pagination="1675 - 1686" refId="ref2807" refString="Anker, A., Poddoubtchenko, D. &amp; Marin, I. (2006) On the presence of the alpheid shrimp genus Bermudacaris Anker and Iliffe, 2000 (Crustacea: Decapoda: Caridea) in the Pacific Ocean, with description of a new species from Vietnam. Journal of Natural History, 40, 1675 - 1686. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930600937734" type="journal article" year="2006">
Anker 
<emphasis box="[670,718,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">et al</emphasis>
. 2006
</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 3a, e); in addition, at least one of them can be seen in some photographs of the lateral view of the specimen (A. Anker, pers. obs.). However, their number, length, shape and exact position should be eventually confirmed by re-examination of the specimen.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,150,1365]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">
Another previously unknown feature of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Anker, Poddoubtchenko &amp; Marin" authorityYear="2006" box="[645,775,1195,1221]" class="Malacostraca" family="Alpheidae" genus="Bermudacaris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="britayevi">
<emphasis box="[645,775,1195,1221]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">B. britayevi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the low number and the relatively large size of eggs (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[239,1347,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-31@3.[239,1347,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Bermudacaris britayevi Anker, Poddoubtchenko &amp; Marin, 2006, ovigerous female (cl 3.0 mm) from Guam, Mariana Islands (FLMNH UF 54550), living shrimp shortly after collection: A—left lateral view; eggs (developing embryos) shed; B—right lateral view. Photographs by the author." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4729437" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4729437/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
), suggesting an abbreviated larval development. At least two species in the related genus 
<taxonomicName authority="De Man, 1888" authorityName="De Man" authorityYear="1888" class="Malacostraca" family="Alpheidae" genus="Automate" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1220,1327,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">Automate</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="De Man, J. G." pageId="5" pageNumber="59" pagination="215 - 600" refId="ref3026" refString="De Man, J. G. (1888) Bericht uber die von Herrn Dr. J. Brock im indischen Archipel gesammelten Decapoden und Stomatopoden. Archiv fur Naturgeschichte, 53, 215 - 600., pls. 7 - 22 a. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 4747" type="journal article" year="1888">De Man, 1888</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
are known to have large to very large eggs, in the latter case indicating a highly abbreviated or semi-direct development (A. Anker, pers. obs.). Therefore, this phenomenon may be not that uncommon among the so-called “lower” alpheids.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
